24:06.500 --> 24:10.580
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

24:26.720 --> 24:32.220
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

24:35.220 --> 24:36.680
And here are your hosts.

24:41.040 --> 24:42.840
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon.

24:43.180 --> 24:45.960
Gordon Dickson has been turning out popular science fiction for over three decades.

24:46.380 --> 24:49.780
During that time he's published around 40 novels and over 150 short stories.

24:49.940 --> 24:55.280
And he's presently at work on his massive series The Childe Cycle, which will be around 13 novels when completed.

24:55.700 --> 24:59.020
We ask Dickson if he gets tired of writing, and if it's hard for him to write.

24:59.640 --> 25:02.540
Any art requires an instant amount

25:02.540 --> 25:09.400
of work. And who hasn't said that the

25:09.400 --> 25:19.060
definition of art was the taking of infinite things or words without a fact. But
the point is, the person doing it enjoys it or he doesn't do it.

25:22.380 --> 25:24.420
I'm fascinated with the work I do.

25:28.600 --> 25:43.500
You wonder, for example, how a concert pianist can practice five hours a day,
week after week, month after month, year after year. You think if you're a non

25:43.500 --> 25:55.200
-piano player or if you had piano playing lessons pushed on you and didn't like
them when you were young, that this must be a self-imposed agony. It is. It's a

25:55.200 --> 26:05.480
sheer pleasure for him to get things just right. And this, of course, is the
battle cry of the artist. It's to get things just right. When we asked Dickson if

26:05.480 --> 26:14.360
he has to do a lot of rewriting, he alluded to a book he had just finished and
that should be published soon, the final encyclopedia. I write and rewrite and

26:14.360 --> 26:24.060
rewrite and rewrite again. This last book, sections of it were

26:24.060 --> 26:35.580
written once and barely touched again. Other sections were written in notable
times. I really couldn't tell you how many, ten or more, ten, fifteen times to

26:35.580 --> 26:47.220
get it just right. I can't re-read anything I've written without picking up a
pencil and starting to correct and improve it. It's instinctive. Most writers

26:47.220 --> 26:57.940
have this kind of reaction to a certain extent, although some rewrite more, some
rewrite less. There is a type of writer that doesn't rewrite but instead sits

26:57.940 --> 27:08.500
and does nothing for a long time and then sits down and does it just the way he
or she wants it. And that possibly is the hardest work of all because it's all

27:08.500 --> 27:20.260
being done in the end. I do it on paper. And of course, the fact that I use a
computer to write with Valdez makes it that much easier, makes it that much

27:20.260 --> 27:28.680
faster. Dickson says that science fiction has developed over the years, a natural
progression from the hardware stories of the late 20s and early 30s. What was

27:28.680 --> 27:41.940
printed in the late 1920s and the early 1930s went through a period of
development when John Gamble took over his founding and the concept of the hard

27:41.940 --> 27:55.860
science fiction story and also something else, the idea story, which is
essentially a thematic science fiction story. It began with John in the 30s. And

27:55.860 --> 28:07.620
that period has developed and gone on. They were originally hardware stories,
originally science fiction. And that's, it's gone from hard science to

28:07.620 --> 28:20.180
essentially soft science. In other words, the subject, the scientific element,
has gone from physics and chemistry to, or rather went from physics and

28:20.180 --> 28:33.820
chemistry into psychology and sociology and things like that. And with the
emergence in the 60s of the excellent crop of women writers who have almost

28:33.820 --> 28:50.860
dominated the field since then, we've had the introduction of character into our
stories. We have become more, much more stories of human interest. As has been

28:50.860 --> 28:57.160
pointed out and said, we've been exploring the inner universe as much as we've
been exploring the outer universe, perhaps more.

29:04.700 --> 29:12.920
